===Anime===
{{see also|List of Descending Stories: Showa Genroku Rakugo Shinju episodes}}
The seventh and eighth volumes of the manga included a 2-episode original [[anime]] DVD entitled {{nihongo|''Yotarō-hen Zenko-pen''|与太郎放浪篇・前後編||lit. "Yotarō Arc Part I and II"}} produced by [[Studio Deen]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rakugo-shinju-anime.jp/news/index.html|title=アニメ「昭和元禄落語心中」|website=アニメ「昭和元禄落語心中」|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref>

An anime television adaptation also produced by Studio Deen premiered on January 9, 2016. It was directed by Mamoru Hatakeyama and written by Jun Kumagai, with music by Kana Shibue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-11-11/showa-genroku-rakugo-shinju-tv-anime-video-reveals-january-8-debut/.95234|title=Shōwa Genroku Rakugo Shinjū TV Anime's Video Reveals January 8 Debut|website=Anime News Network|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> Three promotional videos were released on [[King Records (Japan)|KING RECORDS]]'s YouTube page prior to the anime's premiere: the first on October 6, 2015,<ref>{{Citation|last=KING RECORDS|title=TVアニメ「昭和元禄落語心中」PV①　rakugo shinju animation PV1|date=6 October 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t9fWDQ9e4no|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> the second on 10 November 2015,<ref>{{Citation|last=KING RECORDS|title=TVアニメ「昭和元禄落語心中」PV②　rakugo shinju animation PV2|date=10 November 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W137rrbpdkA&feature=youtu.be|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> and the final PV on December 14, 2015.<ref>{{Citation|last=KING RECORDS|title=TVアニメ「昭和元禄落語心中」PV③　rakugo shinju animation PV3|date=14 December 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=79-t5S8-3Xg&feature=youtu.be|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> The opening theme of the first season was {{nihongo|"Usurai Shinjū"|薄ら氷心中||lit. "Thin-ice Double Suicide"}} composed by [[Ringo Sheena|Sheena Ringo]] and performed by [[Megumi Hayashibara]].<ref>{{Citation|last=KING RECORDS|title=林原めぐみ「薄ら氷心中」Music Video|date=7 January 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a_UxWeBT1BY&feature=youtu.be|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> [[Crunchyroll]] added the anime to its simulcast stream in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2016/01/08/crunchyroll-to-simulcast-showa-genroku-rakugo-shinju-anime|title=Crunchyroll to Simulcast "Showa Genroku Rakugo Shinju" Anime|website=Crunchyroll|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref> The first season has been licensed for a UK release by [[Anime Limited]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-10-30/anime-limited-acquisitions/.108280|title=Anime Limited Acquisitions (Updated 4)|website=Anime News Network|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref>

An announcement revealing the anime's second season was posted on the creator's Twitter account.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-04-01/showa-genroku-rakugo-shinju-anime-gets-2nd-season/.100561|title=Shōwa Genroku Rakugo Shinjū Anime Gets 2nd Season|date=1 April 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=1 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2016-04-02/showa-genroku-rakugo-shinju-sukeroku-futatabi-hen-anime-moves-to-modern-day/.100570|title=Shōwa Genroku Rakugo Shinjū: Sukeroku Futatabi-hen Anime Moves to Modern Day|date=2 April 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref> The second season, titled {{nihongo|''Descending Stories: Shōwa Genroku Rakugo Shinjū''|昭和元禄落語心中～助六再び篇～|Shōwa Genroku Rakugo Shinjū: Sukeroku Futatabi-hen}}, premiered on January 7, 2017.<ref name="S2Year">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-08-05/showa-genroku-rakugo-shinju-anime-season-2-premieres-in-january/.105044|title=Shōwa Genroku Rakugo Shinjū Anime Season 2 Premieres in January|date=5 August 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref><ref name="S2AirDate">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2016-11-18/showa-genroku-rakugo-shinju-anime-2nd-season-premieres-on-january-6/.108967|title=Shōwa Genroku Rakugo Shinjū Anime's 2nd Season Premieres on January 6|date=18 November 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref> The staff from the first season reprised their roles in the second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-11-25/showa-genroku-rakugo-shinju-anime-2nd-season-reveals-staff-cast-visual-ad/.109184|title=Shōwa Genroku Rakugo Shinjū Anime's 2nd Season Reveals Staff, Cast, Visual, Ad|date=25 November 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> The opening theme of the second season was {{nihongo|"Imawa no Shinigami"|今際の死神||lit. "The Death in His Dying Moment"}} composed by Sheena Ringo and performed by [[Megumi Hayashibara]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Komatsu|first=Mikikazu|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2016/12/22-1/megumi-hayashibara-and-sheena-ringo-team-up-again-for-rakugo-shinju-new-op-song|title=Megumi Hayashibara and Sheena Ringo Team Up Again for "Rakugo Shinju" New OP Song|date=22 December 2016|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|accessdate=22 December 2016}}</ref>

===Live-action series===
[[NHK]] announced in July 2018 that a live-action series adaptation has been green-lit. The live-action series is directed by [[Yuki Tanada]], Makoto Kiyohiro and Tatsuo Kobayashi, with scripts written by Daisuke Habara, music by Takatsugu Muramatsu and rakugo supervision by Kyōtarō Yanagiya. [[Masaki Okada]], [[Ryō Ryūsei]], [[Riko Narumi]], [[Aya Ōmasa]] and [[Ikusaburo Yamazaki]] are portraying Yakumo, Yotarō, Konatsu, Miyokichi and Sukeroku, respectively.<ref name="DramaSeriesAnc">{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-07-04/descending-stories-showa-genroku-rakugo-shinju-manga-gets-live-action-series/.133782|title=Descending Stories: Showa Genroku Rakugo Shinju Manga Gets Live-Action Series|date=July 4, 2018|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref>

==Reception==
It was nominated for the 5th [[Manga Taishō]], receiving 49 points and placing 4th among the fifteen nominees.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-03-23/hiromu-arakawa-silver-spoon-wins-5th-manga-taisho-award|title= Hiromu Arakawa's Silver Spoon Wins 5th Manga Taisho Award|date= 23 March 2012|accessdate= 5 May 2014|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> It was also nominated for the 17th [[Tezuka Osamu Cultural Prize]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-02-26/17th-tezuka-osamu-cultural-prize-nominees-announced|title= 17th Tezuka Osamu Cultural Prize Nominees Announced|date= 26 February 2013|accessdate= 5 May 2014|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> It was number two on the 2012 ''Kono Manga ga Sugoi!'' Top 20 Manga for Female Readers survey<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2011-12-08/top-manga-ranked-by-kono-manga-ga-sugoi-2012-voters|title= Top Manga Ranked by Kono Manga ga Sugoi 2012 Voters|date= 8 December 2011|accessdate= 5 May 2014|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> and it was number fourteen in the 2013 edition.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-12-10/top-manga-ranked-by-kono-manga-ga-sugoi-2013-voters|title= Top Manga Ranked by Kono Manga ga Sugoi 2013 Voters|date= 10 December 2012|accessdate= 5 May 2014|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> It was also number seven in the 2013 [[Natalie (website)|Comic Natalie]] Grand Prize<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-09-18/nami-sano-sakamoto-desu-ga-manga-wins-comic-natalie-grand-prize|title= Nami Sano's Sakamoto desu ga? Manga Wins Comic Natalie Grand Prize|date= 18 September 2013|accessdate= 6 May 2014|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> and it won an Excellence Award for manga at the 17th [[Japan Media Arts Festival]] Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-12-05/jojolion-manga-wins-media-arts-award|title=  Jojolion Manga Wins Media Arts Award|date= 5 December 2013|accessdate= 5 May 2014|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> It also won the 38th [[Kodansha Manga Award]] for Best General Manga.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-05-08/yo-kai-watch-baby-steps-win-38th-kodansha-manga-awards|title= Yo-kai Watch, Baby Steps Win 38th Kodansha Manga Awards|date= 8 May 2014|accessdate= 16 November 2014|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> The manga won Kumota the New Creator Prize category of the 21st [[Tezuka Osamu Cultural Prize]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hana ni Somu Manga Wins 21st Tezuka Osamu Cultural Prize's Top Award|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-04-25/hana-ni-somu-manga-wins-21st-tezuka-osamu-cultural-prize-top-award/.115257|website=Anime News Network|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>

Volume 3 sold 24,541 copies by October 7, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-10-10/japanese-comic-ranking-october-1-7|title= Japanese Comic Ranking, October 1–7|date= 10 October 2012|accessdate= 5 May 2014|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref>

Nick Creamer from ''[[Anime News Network]]'' gave the first season an "A" score, describing it as "An intentionally theatrical tragedy, staged something like a rakugo performance itself", and praising its "Strong underlying narrative to gorgeous direction and top-tier performances."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Creamer|first1=Nick|title=Shōwa Genroku Rakugo Shinjū [Episodes 1-13 Streaming]|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/showa-genroku-rakugo-shinju-episodes-1-13-streaming/.100900|website=Anime News Network|accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref>

