{{advert|date=August 2017}} {{lowercase title}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}} {{Infobox website | name = Issuu | favicon = | logo = [[File:Issuu-logo-horizontal.png|frameless]] | screenshot = | caption = You Publish | url = https://issuu.com | commercial = Yes | type = [[Electronic publishing]] | registration = | owner = | language = 30 languages<ref name=Perez/> | author = Michael Hansen, Ruben Bjerg Hansen, Mikkel Jensen, and Martin Ferro-Thomsen | launch date = December 2007 | current status = Active | revenue = | alexa = {{DecreasePositive}} 821 ({{as of|2017|12|4|alt=December 2017}})<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/issuu.com |title=issuu.com Site Info |publisher=Alexa Internet |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref> }} '''Issuu''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɪ|s|.|j|uː}}) is an [[electronic publishing]] platform.<ref name="Bloomberg">{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=39836841 |title=Company Overview of Issuu, Inc. |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref>
==History== Issuu was founded in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]] in 2006<ref name="Bloomberg" /> by Michael and Ruben Bjerg Hansen, Mikkel Jensen, and Martin Ferro-Thomsen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://issuu.com/about |title=About issuu |publisher=issuu.com |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref> Its [[software]] was used by several [[online publication]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/02/garden/the-thriving-online-shelter-magazine-industry.html?pagewanted=all |title=The Thriving (Online) Shelter Magazine Industry |author=Steven Kurutz |publisher=New York Times |date=1 June 2011 |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref> By 2013, [[page view]]s for the company reached about seven to eight billion per month.<ref name=Roush /> Publications are available in thirty different languages. In 2014, the company released '''Clip''', a tool that allows readers to take a snapshot of any part of a publication and share that on [[social media]] or through [[email]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thenextweb.com/apps/2014/07/09/issuu-launches-clip-help-users-publishers-share-best-16m-publications/ |title=Issuu launches Clip to help users and publishers share the best of its 16m publications |author=Martin Bryant |publisher=The Next Web |date=9 July 2014 |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref> That year the company had around 80 million monthly [[unique visitor]]s, with 32 million monthly arriving from [[Web search query|web]] or [[mobile search]]es.<ref name=Perez>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/10/03/issuu-brings-its-youtube-for-magazines-to-the-iphone-and-ipad/ |title=issuu Brings its "YouTube for Magazines" to the iPhone and iPad |author=Sarah Perez |publisher=TechCrunch |date=3 October 2014 |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2014/07/14/issuu-raises-10m-to-become-youtube-for-catalogs-magazines/|title=Issuu Raises $10M to Become ‘YouTube’ for Catalogs, Magazines|first=Lora|last=Kolodny|publisher=}}</ref> In 2014 Issuu also partnered with LinkedIn, which built-in Issuu magazine integration into basic LinkedIn profiles.<ref name="businessinsider.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/linkedin-issuu-embed-partnership-2014-2?op=1|title=You Can Use This New LinkedIn Feature To Highlight Your Work And Make Your Profile Pop|publisher=}}</ref> In 2015 the number was around 85 million unique visitors per month, with 21 million publications publishing through Issuu (amounting to about 15,000 new publications per day).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlinesocialmedia.net/20150219/issuu-has-85m-users-with-magazines-by-pdf/|title=Issuu has 85M users with magazines by PDF - Online Social Media|publisher=}}</ref>
In early 2013, the company opened an office in [[Palo Alto, California]] and appointed CEO Joe Hyrkin, formerly of Reverb, Trinity Ventures, and [[Yahoo!]], to helm its [[Silicon Valley]] operations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/digital/content-and-e-books/article/59118-fast-growing-issuu-appoints-joe-hyrkin-ceo.html |title=Fast Growing issuu Appoints Joe Hyrkin CEO |author=Calvin Reid |publisher=Publishers Weekly |date=16 September 2013 |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2015/05/08/joe-hyrkin-how-to-manage/|title=How to be more bossy at work (in a good way)|date=8 May 2015|publisher=}}</ref> The company soon moved its headquarters to the Palo Alto location.<ref name=Roush>{{cite web|url=http://www.xconomy.com/san-francisco/2013/12/04/issuu-now-california-based-helps-niche-publishers-go-digital/|title=Issuu, Now California-Based, Helps Niche Publishers Go Digital - Xconomy|date=4 December 2013|publisher=}}</ref> Upon the move, the founders of Issuu stated that they chose the city as they saw social media and digital distribution partnerships as the key to its growth, rather than focusing mostly on publishing relationships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2013/09/27/cassidy-issuu-shows-silicon-valleys-vital-role-in-global-commerce/|title=Cassidy: Issuu shows Silicon Valley’s vital role in global commerce – The Mercury News|publisher=}}</ref>
==Finances and partnerships== In July 2014, Issuu raised $10 million in a Series B round to bring the total capital it has raised since it was founded to $21.5 million. That round of investment was led by [[KDDI]] and Sunstone.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hottopics.ht/stories/consumer/issuu-changing-digital-content-market/ |title=Is this the future of digital content for publishers? |author=Viral Shah |publisher=Hot Topics |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref> In 2012 Issuu partnered with Peecho, to embed a cloud printing button into Issuu publication documents. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/apps/2012/04/11/peecho-brings-its-cloud-print-button-to-issuus-vast-online-document-library/|title=Peecho Brings its Cloud Print Button to Issuu - The Next Web|first=Martin|last=Bryant|date=11 April 2012|publisher=}}</ref> In 2013 Issuu acquired publishing software maker Magma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2013/03/05/issuu-hits-10-million-digital-publications-acquires-publishing-software-maker-magma/|title=Issuu Hits 10 Million Publication, Buys Software Firm Magma|first=Robin|last=Wauters|date=5 March 2013|publisher=}}</ref> In 2014 Issuu partnered with LinkedIn, which built in Issuu magazine integration into basic LinkedIn profiles. <ref name="businessinsider.com"/> In January 2016, [[Micromedia Publications]] began publishing its seven weekly newspapers through the Issuu service.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://issuu.com/micromediapubs/stacks |title=Micromedia issuu page |publisher=issuu.com |accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref>
==Apps== In 2014 Issuu released its iOS app to access Issuu on Apple devices. The app includes an offline reading list function that allows users to read from the Issuu app without being online. The app can also stack publications back to back so that they can be read in succession.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://appadvice.com/appnn/2014/10/shelf-control-free-magazines-issues-are-right-at-your-fingertips-with-issuu-for-ios|title=Shelf Control: Free magazine issues are right at your fingertips with Issuu for iOS|first=AppAdvice Staff|last=Author|publisher=}}</ref> Initially the app was released on Android in January, and received between one and five million downloads over the front part of 2014.<ref name=Perez /> Previous to the launch of the company’s 2014 apps, Apple had rejected an app from Issuu three times during 2009 (before the company expanded into the US).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/issuu-gets-android-app/|title=Magazine reader Issuu joins the Android Army, offers 15 million publications|date=21 January 2014|publisher=}}</ref>
==Recognition== In 2008, the site was a [[South by Southwest]] (SXSW) finalist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/03/sxsw-web-awards/ |title=Gowalla Tops Foursquare at SXSW Web Awards (But Benson Smokes 'em All) |author=Michael Calore |publisher=Wired |date=14 March 2010 |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref> In 2009, Issuu was named one of ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]''&apos;s 50 Best Websites.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1918031_1918016_1918004,00.html |title=50 Best Websites 2009 |author=Adam Fisher |publisher=Time |date=24 August 2009 |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref> Since then, Issuu has hosted the scam site 1340 Art Magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://1340art.com/|title=1340Art - International art Magazine.|website=1340Art - International art Magazine.}}</ref> Despite alarms raised since at least 2017,<ref>https://www.agora-gallery.com/advice/blog/2017/05/25/how-to-recognize-art-scam/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://creators.mn.co/posts/1301726|title=Mighty Creators|website=Mighty Creators}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wetcanvas.com/forums/showthread.php?t=1430470|title=1340art magazine, possible scam? - WetCanvas|website=www.wetcanvas.com}}</ref> over submission fees to a nominally existent magazine, and uncompensated sublicensing of submitted art, Issuu has not posted a warning or issued a statement regarding the matter, as of April 2018. The company began offering paid subscriptions in October of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://goodereader.com/blog/digital-magazine-news/issuu-unveils-paid-subscriptions|title=Issuu Unveils Paid Subscriptions|website=goodereader.com}}</ref> By April 2018, Issuu app users were reporting unauthorized charges on their credit cards for up to $420.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sitejabber.com/reviews/issuu.com|title=ISSUU Reviews - 1.4 Stars|website=www.sitejabber.com}}</ref>
