[[File:Tirelli Costumi.png|thumbnail|Logo]] '''Tirelli Costumi Roma''' is a [[Rome]]-based costume house, which supplies period costumes to motion picture productions. It was founded by Umberto Tirelli in 1964, following Tirelli's apprenticeship as a costume maker on ''[[The Leopard (1963 film)|The Leopard]]''.<ref>[http://www.tirelli-costumi.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1&Itemid=9 Tirelli Costumi History]</ref><ref>[http://www.tirelli-costumi.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4&Itemid=11 The Founder Umberto Tirelli]</ref>
In addition to their film work, Tirelli Costumi has supplied and created costumes for stage productions. Their first was a production of ''[[Tosca]]'' at [[Teatro dell'Opera di Roma|Teatro dell'Opera]], a production directed by Mauro Bolognini with costumes by Anna Anni. [[Teatro Comunale Florence|Teatro del Maggio Musicale Fiorentino]], [[Teatro Comunale di Bologna]], [[Sferisterio di Macerata]], [[La Fenice]] in [[Venice]], [[La Scala]] in [[Milan]], [[Teatro Regio (Parma)|Teatro Regio]] in [[Parma, Italy|Parma]], [[Teatro di San Carlo]] in [[Naples]], [[Teatro Verdi (Salerno)|Teatro Municipale Giuseppe Verdi]] in [[Salerno]], [[Teatro Massimo Bellini]] in [[Catania]], [[Teatro Petruzzelli]] in [[Bari]], [[Teatro de la Maestranza]] in [[Seville]], [[Teatro Massimo]] in [[Palermo]], [[Teatro Comunale di Ferrara|Teatro Comunale]] in [[Ferrara]], [[Teatro delle Muse]] in [[Ancona]], [[Teatro Flavio Vespasiano]] in [[Rieti]], Teatro di Palma in [[Majorca]], [[Teatro Pérez Galdós]] on [[Gran Canaria]], [[Théâtre du Capitole]] in [[Toulouse]], the [[Liceu]] in [[Barcelona]], [[Teatro Colón]] in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Municipal Theatre of Santiago|Teatro Municipal]] in [[Santiago]], the [[New National Theatre Tokyo|New National Theatre]] in [[Tokyo]], the [[Tel Aviv Performing Arts Center|Israeli Opera House]] in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[Royal Opera House Muscat|Royal Opera House]] in [[Muscat, Oman]]. Productions at the [[Festival Internacional de Santander]], [[Maggio Musicale Fiorentino]], the [[Ravenna Festival]] and [[Bilbao#Culture|Olbe A.B.A.O. Bilbao]] have utilized Tirelli garments.
