[[File:Almeria 9.jpg|thumb|right|Buildings used for ''[[The Good, the Bad and the Ugly]]'']] [[File:El Condor Almeria.jpg|thumb|right|The fortress used in ''[[El Condor (film)|El Condor]]'']] '''Western Leone''' is a [[Western (genre)|Western]]-style theme park in the province of [[Province of Almería|Almeria]], [[Andalusia]] (Spain). Located at the 378.9&nbsp;km mark on the [[Autovía A-92|A-92 motorway]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kessler |first1=Michael |last2=McLean |first2=Mary |last3=Renouf |first3=Norman |editor1-last=Harmsen |editor1-first=Debbie |title=Fodor's Seville, Granada & Andalusia |edition=1st |year=2008 |publisher=[[Fodor's|Fodor's Travel]] |location=New York, United States |isbn=978-1-4000-1868-0 |page=155 |chapter=The Costa del Sol|display-authors=etal}}</ref> it is the smallest of three such theme parks in the [[Tabernas Desert]]; the other two are [[Mini Hollywood]] and [[Texas Hollywood]]. Western Leone was originally built to film [[Sergio Leone]]'s ''[[Once Upon a Time in the West]]'' (1968);<ref name=foot>{{cite book |last1=Symington |first1=Andy |title=Footprint Andalucía |edition=5th |date=April 2007 |publisher=[[Footprint]] |location=Bath, United Kingdom |isbn=978-1-904777-63-2 |page=412 |chapter=Excursions The Wild West}}</ref> the large red house, around which much of the scenes in the film revolve, is maintained as an attraction, along with other buildings of a Western town.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McCarthy |first=Andrew |authorlink=Andrew McCarthy |date=April 2007 |title=The Good, The Bad, & The Ugly |journal=[[National Geographic Traveler]] |page=80 |location=New York, United States |publisher=[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] |issn=0747-0932 |accessdate=April 12, 2011 |url=http://www.andrewmccarthy.com/overlays/writing_ngt_spain.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xtCmAFXa |archivedate=April 12, 2011}}</ref> It has also been used to film other [[spaghetti western]]s.<ref name=foot />
In 1970, a fortress was built a short distance from Western Leone. This structure was used as a set for ''[[El Condor (1970 film)|El Condor]]'' and later films. The fortress fell into disrepair by 1986.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Moya |first1=José Enrique Martínez |title=Almería, un Mundo de Película |trans-title=Almería, A World of Film |series=Almería y Los Almerienses |volume=11 |year=1999 |publisher=Almería Studies Institute |location=Almeria, Spain |language=Spanish |isbn=84-8108-169-8 |page=367 |trans-chapter=The Fortress of ''El Condor'' |chapter=La Fortaleza de «El Cóndor»}}</ref>
